result.execSummary:
The defendant Jackueline M Brewster was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft - County Ordinance. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Fine to be paid at $20.00 per month commencing 09/01/2015 and each month thereafter or penalty of 4 days jail for non-payment. Defendant may also perform Community Service at the rate of $10.00/hr for fine. Must be completed and proof of completion filed with court within 60 days.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Jackueline M Brewster in court with Attorney Courtney Lynne Gustafson.   District Attorney's Office Law Intern Konrad Paczuski appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  State moves to amend Count #1 to county ordinance theft 13.102(c)(12).  Defendant enters a no contest plea to amended charge.  Court finds Defendant guilty of amended charge and imposes fine of $217.10 - to be paid at $20.00 per month, commencing 9/1/15, alternate 4 days jail or Defendant may perform community servece at rate of $10.00 per hour and has 60 days to perform such community service.  Count #2 is dismissed and read-in.
